are doing the same thing,

00:00:06,874 --> 00:00:08,942
I don't want to be
the 10,001st.

00:00:08,942 --> 00:00:11,512
Sharks, these bandits cause

00:00:11,512 --> 00:00:13,747
thousands of dollars
in damages a day.

00:00:13,747 --> 00:00:14,982
♪♪

00:00:14,982 --> 00:00:17,584
To wear the crown
is a huge responsibility.

00:00:17,584 --> 00:00:18,352
What?!

00:00:18,352 --> 00:00:19,620
We need help.

00:00:19,620 --> 00:00:21,421
This is like kryptonite
to me.

00:00:21,421 --> 00:00:23,090
Guys,
your marketing sucks.

00:00:24,124 --> 00:00:26,493
Things aren't always
as they look.

00:00:26,493 --> 00:00:27,928
What?!
Wait, wait, wait,
wait, wait.

00:00:27,928 --> 00:00:29,062
Wait a minute!

00:00:34,701 --> 00:00:37,371
♪♪

00:00:37,371 --> 00:00:38,906
Narrator:
First into the Tank

00:00:38,906 --> 00:00:41,842
is a quick and affordable
version of a favorite meal.

00:00:41,842 --> 00:00:49,616
♪♪

00:00:49,616 --> 00:00:50,651
Hey, Sharks!

00:00:50,651 --> 00:00:52,219
I make a lot of dough!

00:00:52,219 --> 00:00:54,288
Pasta dough, baby!
What?!

00:00:54,288 --> 00:00:57,558
I'm Brandon Fay,
and I'm seeking $150,000,

00:00:57,558 --> 00:01:00,227
10% equity of my company.

00:01:00,227 --> 00:01:02,396
Sharks, when you want
to go eat Italian,

00:01:02,396 --> 00:01:04,031
first thing
comes to your mind ‐‐

00:01:04,031 --> 00:01:05,832
"Oh, boy.
I gotta go to a restaurant.

00:01:05,832 --> 00:01:07,968
Even with a reservation,
I'm gonna wait a while."

00:01:07,968 --> 00:01:09,670
Then, the pasta's expensive,

00:01:09,670 --> 00:01:11,872
and then by the time the pasta
finally comes, it's cold.

00:01:11,872 --> 00:01:14,074
It's not even fresh pasta!

00:01:14,074 --> 00:01:17,511
And that's why I started
my company, Pasta by Hudson.

00:01:17,511 --> 00:01:21,114
We're a fast‐casual,
quick‐service, fresh pasta bar

00:01:21,114 --> 00:01:24,785
located in the heart
of New York City!

00:01:24,785 --> 00:01:26,053
So, you look at the menu.

00:01:26,053 --> 00:01:28,355
Step 1 ‐‐ pick a pasta shape,

00:01:28,355 --> 00:01:30,958
like campanelle little bells
or bucatini.

00:01:30,958 --> 00:01:33,026
[ Italian accent ]
Long‐a pasta, like‐a spaghetti.

00:01:33,026 --> 00:01:35,696
[ Normal voice ]
We even have veggie pasta
if you don't want carbs.

00:01:35,696 --> 00:01:37,998
Step 2 ‐‐ pick a sauce!

00:01:37,998 --> 00:01:39,333
We have a carbonara.

00:01:39,333 --> 00:01:41,401
Ridiculously decadent,
creamy sauce

00:01:41,401 --> 00:01:43,670
with a fried egg
sitting right on top,

00:01:43,670 --> 00:01:45,005
smoked applewood bacon.

00:01:45,005 --> 00:01:47,240
Or how about try
our popular alla vodka?

00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:48,542
It's a sweet blend

00:01:48,542 --> 00:01:50,944
of our hand‐crushed tomato sauce
and Alfredo.

00:01:50,944 --> 00:01:52,079
Oh, there's more!

00:01:52,079 --> 00:01:53,714
Step 3 ‐‐
grab an extra if you want,

00:01:53,714 --> 00:01:55,649
everything from shrimp
to garlic toast,

00:01:55,649 --> 00:01:57,451
burrata creamy mozzarella.

00:01:57,451 --> 00:02:00,220
We've got our famous signature
cheesy stuffed meatball.

00:02:00,220 --> 00:02:01,788
You can keep it simple,
you can mix it up.

00:02:01,788 --> 00:02:03,724
You can eat it now,
you can eat it later.

00:02:03,724 --> 00:02:06,326
Come on! Who wants to make
a lot of dough?!

00:02:06,326 --> 00:02:08,662
Yeah!
Whoa!

00:02:08,662 --> 00:02:12,065
Now, in front of you, you got
a lot of delicious pasta.

00:02:12,065 --> 00:02:13,233
Let me tell you something ‐‐

00:02:13,233 --> 00:02:15,402
if you cook with love,
people can tell.

00:02:15,402 --> 00:02:17,204
They know right away.
Ohh!

00:02:17,204 --> 00:02:18,338
Mmm.

00:02:18,338 --> 00:02:19,373
That is so good.

00:02:19,373 --> 00:02:20,440
So, allow me, please.

00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:21,541
Excellent.

00:02:21,541 --> 00:02:22,876
Corcoran: This is fabulous.
Pomodoro ‐‐ great.

00:02:22,876 --> 00:02:24,945
What's this here?
Cuban:
Yeah. Gemelli pomodoro.

00:02:24,945 --> 00:02:26,146
Oh, gosh.
Mmm!

00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:27,581
Unh!

00:02:27,581 --> 00:02:29,316
Oh, wow. The meatball.
Corcoran: My God.

00:02:29,316 --> 00:02:31,652
Let me tell you ‐‐ this is
the best meatball I've ever had.

00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:33,453
Why don't you tell us
about you,

00:02:33,453 --> 00:02:36,556
how you started this business,
and what you were doing before?

00:02:36,556 --> 00:02:37,858
Well, first of all,
I'm the son

00:02:37,858 --> 00:02:40,794
of two New York City
police officers.

00:02:40,794 --> 00:02:43,530
My parents were actually
Bridge and Tunnel officers.
Really?

00:02:43,530 --> 00:02:44,631
My dad was a sergeant.

00:02:44,631 --> 00:02:46,400
But [Smooches] he's since gone,

00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:48,168
but we love him and miss him
every day of my life.

00:02:48,168 --> 00:02:49,636
Are you
an Italian extract?

00:02:49,636 --> 00:02:51,138
You don't look Italian
at all.

00:02:51,138 --> 00:02:52,372
I'm Jewish and Irish!

00:02:52,372 --> 00:02:53,907
‐Nice!
‐Come on.
‐Irish?

00:02:53,907 --> 00:02:55,909
They make
the best Italian food.

00:02:55,909 --> 00:02:57,077
Make the best Italian food.

00:02:57,077 --> 00:02:58,845
Help me visualize
your operation.

00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:00,547
Is it a store?
Is it a truck?

00:03:00,547 --> 00:03:01,815
So, we actually have
a picture.

00:03:01,815 --> 00:03:03,316
I can show you
what it looks like.
Good.

00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:05,218
We've got 390 square feet.

00:03:05,218 --> 00:03:06,687
It's one store?

00:03:06,687 --> 00:03:07,821
It's one store right now.

00:03:07,821 --> 00:03:08,922
Where is that located?

00:03:08,922 --> 00:03:10,791
We're located
in Columbus Circle.

00:03:10,791 --> 00:03:13,560
We're in the eighth‐busiest
transit hub in New York City.

00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:15,629
24 million people a year
go through there.

00:03:15,629 --> 00:03:18,198
When I walk up here for lunch,
what am I spending?

00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:20,534
So, your pomodoro starts
at $8.95.

00:03:20,534 --> 00:03:23,136
Then the rest of the dishes,
about $12 to $13.

00:03:23,136 --> 00:03:25,772
Are you a chef? How did you
come up with this idea?

00:03:25,772 --> 00:03:26,873
So, no training experience.

00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:29,076
I ran
one of the busiest restaurants,

00:03:29,076 --> 00:03:30,243
not only in New York City,

00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:31,678
but in pretty much
the United States.

00:03:31,678 --> 00:03:33,013
You were the manager
of the restaurant?

00:03:33,013 --> 00:03:34,881
I was managing director,
130 employees.

00:03:34,881 --> 00:03:36,583
And then when you work in
a restaurant your
whole entire life ‐‐

00:03:36,583 --> 00:03:38,218
I'm almost 25 years
in the industry ‐‐

00:03:38,218 --> 00:03:39,419
you pick up a few things.

00:03:39,419 --> 00:03:40,887
So, what are
your sales to date?

00:03:40,887 --> 00:03:44,291
Year to date,
we're at about $590,000.

00:03:44,291 --> 00:03:45,692
And your overhead
is what?

00:03:45,692 --> 00:03:46,960
$55,000 a month.

00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:48,295
Is that
your business model,

00:03:48,295 --> 00:03:50,697
to continue opening
within food courts,

00:03:50,697 --> 00:03:52,833
where the business
tends to come to you

00:03:52,833 --> 00:03:54,234
because there's
so many people going by?

00:03:54,234 --> 00:03:55,268
You hit the nail
on the head.

00:03:55,268 --> 00:03:56,903
So, my business plan
is to open up

00:03:56,903 --> 00:03:58,905
in very high‐volume,
high‐foot‐traffic areas.

00:03:58,905 --> 00:04:00,574
Are you profitable now?

00:04:00,574 --> 00:04:02,676
By the end of the year,
we'll probably break even
on the first year.

00:04:02,676 --> 00:04:04,811
By next year, I predict
that I'll at least do ‐‐

00:04:04,811 --> 00:04:08,148
I'll do 1.2, 1.3.

00:04:08,148 --> 00:04:11,518
Is this gonna be expansion
of just you opening locations

00:04:11,518 --> 00:04:12,986
or franchise or both?

00:04:12,986 --> 00:04:15,255
I see us making sure
we build a foundation ‐‐
really solid, right?

00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:17,724
And yes, we do franchising ‐‐
probably a little bit too early,

00:04:17,724 --> 00:04:19,760
but that's something
we can always talk about.

00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:21,194
What's it cost you
to open one?

00:04:21,194 --> 00:04:23,730
So, this one was 350,
but we learned a lot,

00:04:23,730 --> 00:04:25,432
and when I was looking
at possibly doing,

00:04:25,432 --> 00:04:28,168
like, a smaller kiosk, that one
would have been, like, 200.

00:04:28,168 --> 00:04:29,503
Everything gets more efficient.

00:04:29,503 --> 00:04:32,139
So, 350
to get the doors open.

00:04:32,139 --> 00:04:33,540
Brandon...
Yes, sir?

00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:35,442
...I think
it's a genius idea,

00:04:35,442 --> 00:04:37,644
but I have
a personal issue

00:04:37,644 --> 00:04:39,579
on why this may be
a challenge for me.

00:04:39,579 --> 00:04:43,183
I have horrible acid reflux.
Horrible.

00:04:43,183 --> 00:04:44,918
So, you know,
I can't have onions,

00:04:44,918 --> 00:04:46,453
I can't have tomato base.

00:04:46,453 --> 00:04:47,687
This is like kryptonite
to me,

00:04:47,687 --> 00:04:49,122
even though
it was delicious.

00:04:49,122 --> 00:04:50,690
So, unfortunately, I'm out.

00:04:50,690 --> 00:04:51,725
Totally understand.

00:04:51,725 --> 00:04:52,993
Cuban: Do you guys do
delivery at all

00:04:52,993 --> 00:04:54,861
or have an app
where people can pick?

00:04:54,861 --> 00:04:57,764
The blend of my business right
now is actually half of that ‐‐

00:04:57,764 --> 00:04:59,966
almost half is delivery.

00:04:59,966 --> 00:05:01,434
That's good, though, right?
It <i>is</i> good.

00:05:01,434 --> 00:05:03,637
What we're learning is, they do
take a big commission, right?

00:05:03,637 --> 00:05:05,238
Yeah, they take
20, 25%, yeah.

00:05:05,238 --> 00:05:06,873
Yeah.
Does that make sense
for you?

00:05:06,873 --> 00:05:08,809
I am so thankful for
the business they've given me

00:05:08,809 --> 00:05:10,243
because it's huge.

00:05:10,243 --> 00:05:12,546
It opens you up to
a larger market a mile away,

00:05:12,546 --> 00:05:14,381
people that have never
even known I'm there.

00:05:14,381 --> 00:05:16,349
It's about where am I
going in the future and how
big I'm gonna grow this.

00:05:16,349 --> 00:05:17,818
Well, and let's talk about
future, right?

00:05:17,818 --> 00:05:20,954
Because, really, your biggest
future is delivery‐only.

00:05:20,954 --> 00:05:24,124
Like, if I knew that you had
spaghetti squash on there,

00:05:24,124 --> 00:05:27,961
this size with that sauce,
and it was 250 calories,

00:05:27,961 --> 00:05:29,429
I'm ordering every night.

00:05:29,429 --> 00:05:30,831
And they've got
the place ‐‐

00:05:30,831 --> 00:05:33,133
you know, CloudKitchen
and the places like that,

00:05:33,133 --> 00:05:36,536
where you just have the kitchen,
they do the rest.

00:05:36,536 --> 00:05:39,706
I mean, would you be open to
doing just a CloudKitchen?

00:05:39,706 --> 00:05:41,842
Satellite kitchens.
Absolutely.
Yeah.

00:05:41,842 --> 00:05:43,844
'Cause then you have
more of a market going
in other directions.

00:05:43,844 --> 00:05:45,512
You're not there ‐‐
much lower rent

00:05:45,512 --> 00:05:47,113
because those places
aren't storefronts.

00:05:47,113 --> 00:05:49,282
And you can go to more cities
more often, quicker.

00:05:49,282 --> 00:05:51,284
Correct.
Brandon,
the food's spectacular.

00:05:51,284 --> 00:05:52,886
It's a break‐even business.

00:05:52,886 --> 00:05:54,421
It's not franchisable yet.

00:05:54,421 --> 00:05:57,691
You'd have to be making 15%
pre‐tax to franchise.

00:05:57,691 --> 00:05:59,559
You're a ways off for that.

00:05:59,559 --> 00:06:01,628
Too early for me.
I'm out.

00:06:01,628 --> 00:06:04,164
Alright. By the way,
you're more than welcome
to come back in if you want.

00:06:04,164 --> 00:06:06,399
Corcoran: [ Laughs ]
I would love it,
'cause you're Mr. Wonderful.

00:06:06,399 --> 00:06:07,934
Obviously,
your food is fabulous.

00:06:07,934 --> 00:06:09,469
That meatball ‐‐
I wasn't just saying ‐‐

00:06:09,469 --> 00:06:10,737
it's the best meatball
I've ever eaten.

00:06:10,737 --> 00:06:13,306
The best meatball
I've ever eaten ‐‐ by far, okay?

00:06:13,306 --> 00:06:14,441
So I want that recipe.

00:06:14,441 --> 00:06:15,775
Done.
Okay.

00:06:15,775 --> 00:06:17,444
What does it cost you
to make one meatball?

00:06:17,444 --> 00:06:18,745
About 45 cents.

00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:20,180
And what do you
sell them for?

00:06:20,180 --> 00:06:22,148
$4.95.
Wow.

00:06:22,148 --> 00:06:23,383
Do they freeze well?

00:06:23,383 --> 00:06:25,285
Oh, yes. I froze them
and shipped them here.

00:06:25,285 --> 00:06:26,553
Youse two can partner
together...

00:06:26,553 --> 00:06:29,189
It would be great...
...and we could crush this.

00:06:29,189 --> 00:06:30,357
I have a deal for you.
Listen to this.

00:06:30,357 --> 00:06:31,658
We could crush this.

00:06:31,658 --> 00:06:32,993
Hey, be quiet a minute.
I have a deal for you.

00:06:32,993 --> 00:06:35,528
Alright, listen,
if Mark will do it,
I'd go in with Mark.

00:06:35,528 --> 00:06:36,763
While they're going in
with Mark,

00:06:36,763 --> 00:06:38,265
let me suggest
what I'll do.

00:06:38,265 --> 00:06:39,399
Yes, please.
Okay? Alright.

00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:42,369
Mark.
I'll give you the $150,000
for 50%.

00:06:42,369 --> 00:06:43,670
Say that number again.
I couldn't hear you.

00:06:43,670 --> 00:06:45,672
I'll give you $150,000

00:06:45,672 --> 00:06:47,908
for 50%
of your meatball business

00:06:47,908 --> 00:06:49,342
if you'll get it online.

00:06:49,342 --> 00:06:50,477
You can make a fortune.

00:06:50,477 --> 00:06:52,913
[ Laughing ]
Just online meatballs?

00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:54,514
That's an amazing offer.

00:06:54,514 --> 00:06:56,917
The fact that you even
gave me an offer ‐‐ believe
me, that's wonderful.

00:06:56,917 --> 00:06:58,652
Would you mind if I hear
what Lori and Mark have to say?

00:06:58,652 --> 00:07:00,320
I don't mind at all.
Help yourself.

00:07:00,320 --> 00:07:01,855
And I'm considering that.
I only like the meatballs.

00:07:01,855 --> 00:07:03,056
I'm considering everything
because ‐‐

00:07:03,056 --> 00:07:05,025
Are you interested
in going in together?

00:07:05,025 --> 00:07:06,493
Cuban: I want 20%.

00:07:07,694 --> 00:07:09,996
Well, Mark wants 20%,
which means,

00:07:09,996 --> 00:07:11,865
what is that
going to be left for me?

00:07:11,865 --> 00:07:13,166
Right?

00:07:13,166 --> 00:07:14,634
So, I'm gonna ‐‐
[ Italian accent ]
A meatball.

00:07:14,634 --> 00:07:16,069
[ Italian accent ]
A meatball.

00:07:16,069 --> 00:07:17,337
Mark, is that 20%
10, 10?

00:07:17,337 --> 00:07:19,139
No. I need to get to 20.
No, he doesn't want that.

00:07:19,139 --> 00:07:21,107
He wants 20% himself.

00:07:21,107 --> 00:07:22,409
What does that
leave for me?

00:07:22,409 --> 00:07:23,944
Well, let me ask you
something ‐‐ if, hypothetical,

00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:26,413
if I gave you both 15,
and you know I know operations,

00:07:26,413 --> 00:07:27,881
you know I know food,
and I'm gonna crush it,

00:07:27,881 --> 00:07:29,749
are you gonna help me
blow this thing up?

00:07:29,749 --> 00:07:32,252
Yeah, look, I'm not investing
to not help it grow.

00:07:32,252 --> 00:07:33,553
Of course.
Right?

00:07:33,553 --> 00:07:35,822
I'll give you the $150,000,
I want 20%,

00:07:35,822 --> 00:07:37,757
and I have no problem
partnering with Lori.

00:07:37,757 --> 00:07:39,092
The only thing
that I require

00:07:39,092 --> 00:07:41,127
is that we seriously consider
the CloudKitchens,

00:07:41,127 --> 00:07:43,730
'cause that allows us to go into
as many markets as you want.

00:07:43,730 --> 00:07:45,899
If Lori wants to come in
and negotiate something

00:07:45,899 --> 00:07:47,867
on top of that,
I'm kosher with that.

00:07:47,867 --> 00:07:51,504
Well, I liked your $150,000,
15 and 15.

00:07:51,504 --> 00:07:53,206
Why wouldn't you
do that, Mark?

00:07:53,206 --> 00:07:54,574
What do you mean?
Did you hear that?

00:07:54,574 --> 00:07:57,243
Because that's actually
a very good offer to us.

00:07:57,243 --> 00:07:58,345
Not to me.

00:07:58,345 --> 00:08:00,280
Oh, come on. 5%?

00:08:00,280 --> 00:08:01,448
Seriously.

00:08:01,448 --> 00:08:02,949
Just take 10%, then,
Lori.

00:08:02,949 --> 00:08:05,518
But we ‐‐ 10%.

00:08:05,518 --> 00:08:08,989
How much of my money are you
offering him for the 10%?

00:08:08,989 --> 00:08:10,824
Okay, Brandon,
here's what we're gonna do.

00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:13,626
I'm gonna put in 100K,
Lori's gonna put up 50K.

00:08:13,626 --> 00:08:15,328
We're gonna take 30%.

00:08:15,328 --> 00:08:16,930
I'll keep 20 of it,
she'll keep 10.

00:08:16,930 --> 00:08:18,098
Do we have a deal?

00:08:19,833 --> 00:08:21,801
Alright, I'll do it.
Okay. Deal.

00:08:21,801 --> 00:08:24,170
Corcoran: Wait a minute!
Wait, wait, wait, wait!

00:08:24,170 --> 00:08:25,605
<i>You</i> didn't agree to it.
Do you agree to it?

00:08:25,605 --> 00:08:27,507
Greiner: Done.
I ‐‐ Come on!

00:08:27,507 --> 00:08:29,776
[ Laughter ]

00:08:29,776 --> 00:08:31,778
Yeah, baby! Yeah!

00:08:31,778 --> 00:08:33,246
[ Laughs ]
Yeah!

00:08:33,246 --> 00:08:34,647
Now I'm gonna tell you
something, Brandon ‐‐

00:08:34,647 --> 00:08:35,949
you made a mistake here.

00:08:35,949 --> 00:08:37,283
You had another deal
on the table,

00:08:37,283 --> 00:08:39,619
and you never even
entertained it.

00:08:39,619 --> 00:08:41,821
And, listen, I'm
unbelievably grateful that
