has been given to us.

00:37:37,021 --> 00:37:39,090
Why is that? Is it
'cause you're already
in business with them?

00:37:39,090 --> 00:37:40,358
They know the quality
of our produce.

00:37:40,358 --> 00:37:42,260
Their customers
are coming in saying,

00:37:42,260 --> 00:37:44,996
"I want Evans Farms produce.
It's the best in the world."

00:37:44,996 --> 00:37:47,265
But that's local
'cause they know you, Katey Jo.

00:37:47,265 --> 00:37:49,400
You get the edge
because it's a great product

00:37:49,400 --> 00:37:51,836
and they know the quality
that comes from your farm.

00:37:51,836 --> 00:37:54,105
Once you get to Dallas
and New York

00:37:54,105 --> 00:37:55,373
and everywhere else,

00:37:55,373 --> 00:37:57,776
you don't have
that home‐court advantage.

00:37:57,776 --> 00:37:59,244
You've seen my hustle here.

00:37:59,244 --> 00:38:01,412
I'm unable
to hustle this product yet.

00:38:01,412 --> 00:38:04,282
We're almost
at production capacity on farm.

00:38:04,282 --> 00:38:06,785
I've got to get
to a co‐packer level.

00:38:06,785 --> 00:38:07,886
John: You know what?

00:38:07,886 --> 00:38:09,487
I think you're getting
a lot of demand

00:38:09,487 --> 00:38:12,023
because
you're a local hero.

00:38:12,023 --> 00:38:13,725
And it is gonna be
very hard to scale.

00:38:13,725 --> 00:38:15,160
This is
a super‐tough business.

00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:17,295
One of my best friends
builds the refrigeration

00:38:17,295 --> 00:38:19,697
for Giant and Key Food,

00:38:19,697 --> 00:38:21,166
and he always told me,

00:38:21,166 --> 00:38:24,903
"Promise me you will never
get into refrigerated goods."

00:38:24,903 --> 00:38:27,172
[ Laughs ]
Because it's hard
to ship these things.

00:38:27,172 --> 00:38:28,573
These trucks are
a lot of money,

00:38:28,573 --> 00:38:30,575
as you know,

00:38:30,575 --> 00:38:32,944
and it's very, very,
very difficult.

00:38:32,944 --> 00:38:34,312
I think
you're gonna be okay, though,

00:38:34,312 --> 00:38:36,714
on the farm and locally,
doing what you do.

00:38:36,714 --> 00:38:39,184
Just be just as energetic
as you always are,

00:38:39,184 --> 00:38:41,119
and I wish you luck,
but I'm out.

00:38:41,119 --> 00:38:42,387
Thank you, Daymond.

00:38:42,387 --> 00:38:45,557
Yeah, Katey Jo, the problem is,
to Daymond's point,

00:38:45,557 --> 00:38:46,791
refrigerated's hard.

00:38:46,791 --> 00:38:48,526
Frozen's even worse.

00:38:48,526 --> 00:38:50,128
Because there's
even less space available.

00:38:50,128 --> 00:38:51,196
Guys, I love hard.

00:38:51,196 --> 00:38:53,131
I have no doubt, right?

00:38:53,131 --> 00:38:54,699
I was born for hard.

00:38:54,699 --> 00:38:57,435
Look, Katey Jo, what you've
accomplished is great.

00:38:57,435 --> 00:38:59,237
What I don't think
you have a grasp on

00:38:59,237 --> 00:39:01,272
is what it's gonna take
to scale nationally.

00:39:01,272 --> 00:39:03,641
I know you want a fight. It's
not a fight I want to fight.

00:39:03,641 --> 00:39:06,978
Small‐label ice creams
are the up‐and‐coming marque.

00:39:06,978 --> 00:39:08,947
Look at the margins.
They're the only thing...
You're right.

00:39:08,947 --> 00:39:11,516
And there's 30 of them.
...that's carrying the ice cream
industry right now.

00:39:11,516 --> 00:39:14,886
Big‐box brands ‐‐ the margins
and profits are down.

00:39:14,886 --> 00:39:16,020
You know what?

00:39:16,020 --> 00:39:18,022
When 10,000 people
are doing the same thing,

00:39:18,022 --> 00:39:19,591
I don't want to be
the 10,001st.

00:39:21,125 --> 00:39:22,160
Katey Jo, I'm out.

00:39:23,161 --> 00:39:25,296
Thank you.
Thank you. Congrats.

00:39:25,296 --> 00:39:27,632
Katey Jo,
I love the misfit fruit ideas.

00:39:27,632 --> 00:39:30,435
These are rejected
by their peers.
It's great.

00:39:30,435 --> 00:39:32,237
That strawberry
got kicked off the branch.

00:39:32,237 --> 00:39:33,638
[ Laughs ]

00:39:33,638 --> 00:39:35,807
I look at it as a very difficult
business to invest in

00:39:35,807 --> 00:39:37,208
'cause of its structure.

00:39:37,208 --> 00:39:40,245
Mr. Wonderful, you don't like
easy stuff, either.

00:39:40,245 --> 00:39:42,280
No, no, no.
You're up for the challenge.

00:39:50,989 --> 00:39:52,757
Narrator:
Three Sharks are out.

00:39:52,757 --> 00:39:55,393
Katey Jo has
only two more chances for a deal

00:39:55,393 --> 00:39:58,563
for her ice cream and sorbet
company, The Frozen Farmer.

00:39:58,563 --> 00:39:59,764
It's a family business.

00:39:59,764 --> 00:40:01,332
But, I mean, who's gonna
give you better pricing

00:40:01,332 --> 00:40:03,268
on the ingredients
than the farmer themselves?

00:40:03,268 --> 00:40:05,470
I love the product.
I love your enthusiasm.
I would so much rather
sell this for ‐‐

00:40:05,470 --> 00:40:07,939
But I can't invest
in every business,

00:40:07,939 --> 00:40:10,575
and ice cream is just not
the place I want to be.

00:40:10,575 --> 00:40:12,377
I wish you the best.
I'm out.

00:40:13,611 --> 00:40:14,646
Thank you.

00:40:16,481 --> 00:40:18,249
[ Voice breaking ] Lori.

00:40:20,285 --> 00:40:23,755
You know, I'm not
a huge ice cream person,

00:40:23,755 --> 00:40:26,291
but I have to tell you,

00:40:26,291 --> 00:40:30,495
these ice creams were the best
I've ever had in my entire life.

00:40:30,495 --> 00:40:32,096
The orange creamsicle,

00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:34,299
I thought was one of
the creamiest‐tasting,

00:40:34,299 --> 00:40:36,267
best‐tasting things ever.

00:40:36,267 --> 00:40:38,670
The sorbets are phenomenal.

00:40:38,670 --> 00:40:41,539
So I think that your product
is fantastic.

00:40:41,539 --> 00:40:44,442
I think
with the right packaging ‐‐

00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:46,511
you really need
your packaging to pop.

00:40:46,511 --> 00:40:50,214
I mean, even being called
misfit fruit sorbet

00:40:50,214 --> 00:40:51,449
is kind of interesting,

00:40:51,449 --> 00:40:53,751
because people who care
about the environment

00:40:53,751 --> 00:40:55,653
and not wasting
and using everything

00:40:55,653 --> 00:40:59,624
would get that message almost
immediately from that name.

00:40:59,624 --> 00:41:00,825
It's a great name.

00:41:00,825 --> 00:41:03,127
But it's really, really,
really hard

00:41:03,127 --> 00:41:06,497
to be in the ice cream business,
as they all were saying.

00:41:06,497 --> 00:41:09,801
But yet you have something that
I think is like Blue Ribbon.

00:41:09,801 --> 00:41:11,502
I'm just not sure ‐‐

00:41:11,502 --> 00:41:12,603
Come on, Lori.

00:41:12,603 --> 00:41:16,307
One, I will help you
redo your packaging,

00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:17,775
alright,
no matter what,

00:41:17,775 --> 00:41:19,777
so that you will have
a great label,

00:41:19,777 --> 00:41:22,447
and I'll help you with the name
and the trademark and that.

00:41:22,447 --> 00:41:24,115
Okay.

00:41:24,115 --> 00:41:26,918
I'm gonna offer you
the $125,000...

00:41:26,918 --> 00:41:29,554
♪♪

00:41:29,554 --> 00:41:30,855
...30%.

00:41:30,855 --> 00:41:32,523
But I will give you
the money

00:41:32,523 --> 00:41:37,462
if we can land
a major national chain

00:41:37,462 --> 00:41:38,997
with the product.

00:41:38,997 --> 00:41:40,498
Well, it's good
you said that,

00:41:40,498 --> 00:41:42,667
'cause I've already had talks
with Harris Teeter and Wegmans.

00:41:42,667 --> 00:41:46,337
$125,000 for 30%?

00:41:46,337 --> 00:41:48,373
I wouldn't think about it
too long, Katey Jo.
Yes. Like a Wegmans ‐‐

00:41:48,373 --> 00:41:51,075
Lori, I will do that deal
with you!

00:41:51,075 --> 00:41:53,478
I'm sorry! I know
I'm supposed to negotiate!

00:41:53,478 --> 00:41:55,346
[ Laughter ]
I'm sorry!

00:41:55,346 --> 00:41:57,015
Aaah!

00:41:57,015 --> 00:41:59,817
Oh, my!

00:41:59,817 --> 00:42:01,819
[ Laughs ]

00:42:01,819 --> 00:42:03,287
Congratulations, Katey Jo.
Thank you, guys.

00:42:03,287 --> 00:42:05,023
Thank you all for your time.
O'Leary:
Thank you very much.

00:42:05,023 --> 00:42:07,191
This has been truly an honor.
Oh, it's heavy!

00:42:07,191 --> 00:42:09,694
To wear the crown
is a huge responsibility.

00:42:11,896 --> 00:42:14,799
Getting this deal today means
everything to our business.

00:42:14,799 --> 00:42:17,702
I mean, who would have ever
thought in a million years

00:42:17,702 --> 00:42:20,371
that a farmer's wife
from Bridgeville, Delaware,

00:42:20,371 --> 00:42:23,674
would end up on "Shark Tank"
and getting a deal with Lori?

00:42:23,674 --> 00:42:25,977
And I'm just
so incredibly grateful.

00:42:32,050 --> 00:42:40,458
♪♪

00:42:40,458 --> 00:42:48,833
♪♪

